.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1333&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=2a13c132258e1eb469e86f7a2ca7b918 2000w"
                fetchpriority="high"    />


            
            
<figcaption class="attribution">
    
        <span class="attribution__credit">
        <span class="a11y">Credit: </span>
        Photo illustration by Shoshana Gordon/ProPublica. Source images: Obtained by ProPublica and Verite News, Kathleen Flynn for ProPublica.
    </span>
    
    
    </figcaption>

        </figure>
            <div class="opener__topic-title-dek-wrapper">

                    <span class="opener__topics">
            <a class="opener__topics-link" href="https://www.propublica.org/topics/criminal-justice">Criminal Justice</a>
        </span>
    
    <h1
        class="opener__hed "
        
    >        An Unconstitutional “Jim Crow Jury” Sent Him to Prison for Life. A New Law Aims to Keep Him There.
    </h1>

    <h2
        class="opener__dek"
        style="display: none"        >
            Five years ago, the Supreme Court decided that nonunanimous jury verdicts are unconstitutional. But for this Louisiana prisoner — and hundreds of others — “tough on crime” state leaders have ensured that doesn’t change anything.
    </h2>
    </div> <!-- Close .opener__topic-title-dek-wrapper -->

</div>
        
<div class="article-meta-1
     article-meta-1--left     " data-pp-location="article meta">

    <span class="article-meta-1__byline" data-pp-location="article byine">
        by <span class="name">Richard A. Webster</span>, <a href="https://veritenews.org/">Verite News</a>    </span>
    <time class="article-meta-1__pubdate">
        <time class="timestamp" datetime="2025-08-25EDT05:00">Aug. 25, 2025, 5 a.m. EDT</time>
    </time>

